[moddesc {NaviServer Database Interface}]
[titledesc {Database support and connection pool configuration}]

[description]

The [const nsdb] module provides NaviServer's database integration.  It
connects virtual servers to globally configured database pools and exposes the
database access API used by Tcl code.

[para]
Database support is optional.  Installations that use it load the
[const nsdb] module for a virtual server, register one or more database
drivers, define global database pools, and select which pools are available to
each server.

[para]
For a detailed discussion of NaviServer database configuration, database
pools, handles, and operational considerations, see
[uri ../../manual/files/admin-db.html {Database Access and Configuration}].

[section {Overview}]

NaviServer database configuration consists of four parts:

[list_begin itemized]
[item] The [const nsdb] module is loaded for a virtual server.
[item] Database drivers are registered in [const {ns/db/drivers}].
[item] Database pools are defined globally in [const {ns/db/pools}] and
[const {ns/db/pool/$dbpool}].
[item] A server selects its available pools in [const {ns/server/$server/db}].
[list_end]

[para]
Database pools are global definitions and may be shared by multiple virtual
servers.  The per-server database section determines which of these global
pools are available to a server and which pool is used by default.

[section {Loading the nsdb Module}]

Load [const nsdb] as a per-server module:

[example_begin]
ns_section ns/server/$server/modules {
    ns_param nsdb nsdb
}
[example_end]

[para]
Then select the database pools available to the server:

[example_begin]
ns_section ns/server/$server/db {
    ns_param pools       pool1,pool2,pool3
    ns_param defaultpool pool1
}
[example_end]

[section {Database Drivers}]

Database drivers implement the low-level connection to a specific database
system.  They are external NaviServer modules and must be compiled and
installed separately before they can be loaded.

[para]
The [const {ns/db/drivers}] section maps configuration-defined driver names to
driver implementations:

[example_begin]
ns_section ns/db/drivers {
    ns_param postgres nsdbpg
    ns_param nsoracle nsoracle
}
[example_end]

[para]
The configured driver name is later used by database pools through the
[const driver] parameter.  For example, a pool using the PostgreSQL driver
above would specify [const postgres], not [const nsdbpg].

[example_begin]
ns_section ns/db/pool/pool1 {
    ns_param driver postgres
}
[example_end]

[para]
Driver-specific settings, when needed, are configured below
[const {ns/db/driver/$dbdriver}], where [const {$dbdriver}] is the configured
driver name from [const {ns/db/drivers}].

[example_begin]
ns_section ns/db/driver/postgres {
    ns_param pgbin /usr/lib/postgresql/16/bin/
}
[example_end]

[section {Database Pools}]

Database pools define reusable sets of database connections.  Each pool
specifies the driver, datasource, credentials, connection count, and optional
handle lifetime settings.

[example_begin]
ns_section ns/db/pools {
    ns_param pool1 "Main database pool"
    ns_param pool2 "Secondary database pool"
    ns_param pool3 "Optional third database pool"
}

ns_section ns/db/pool/pool1 {
    ns_param driver         postgres
    ns_param datasource     localhost::dbname
    ns_param user           dbuser
    ns_param password       secret
    ns_param connections    15
    ns_param logminduration 10ms
}
[example_end]

[para]
A pool can be used by multiple virtual servers.  The server-specific
[const {ns/server/$server/db}] section controls which pools are available to a
particular server.

[section {Per-Server Database Configuration}]

The [const {ns/server/$server/db}] section selects the database pools
available to a virtual server.

[example_begin]
ns_section ns/server/$server/db {
    ns_param pools       pool1,pool2,pool3
    ns_param defaultpool pool1
}
[example_end]

[para]
The [const defaultpool] is used when application code requests a database
handle without naming a specific pool.

